Description: Fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and a partly glossy surface. The rear shows one side with impressions of two smaller rows of basketry coil and another side with one larger row of basketry coil, suggesting that the piece was attached between the wall and the lid of a basket. The upper side bears an impression of a square shaped seal and many finger impressions above it. Only the upper right corner is preserved, showing the figure of a standing Amun with the double feather crown, in front of him [J]mn written in hieroglyphs. Amun is holding a wAs-sceptre.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
